 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Replicating Vanderburg & Johnson 2014 using lightkurve"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "[Vanderburg and Johnson 2014](http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014PASP..126..948V) introduced a method for \"Self Flat Fielding\" by tracking how the lightcurve changes with motion of the spacecraft.  \n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook we replicate the K2SFF method using only the `lightkurve` package.  \n",
    "\n",
    "We experiment with several different sources.\n",
    "\n",
    "We start from the Target Pixel File and proceed to a \"systematics corrected\" lightcurve plot similar to the one in the paper and in our companion notebook.  We hope to show the ease-of-use of the new `lightkurve` toolkit, and that it achieves identical performace with published papers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from lightkurve import KeplerTargetPixelFile\n",
    "from lightkurve import SFFCorrector"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "  LightkurveWarning)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "tpf = KeplerTargetPixelFile.from_archive(211901114, campaign=16)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "source": [
    "lc_raw = tpf.to_lightcurve(aperture_mask=VDB_J_mask)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Exlude the first 2.5 days and non-zero quality flags, following Vanderburg & Johnson."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "first_2p5_days = lc_raw.time - lc_raw.time[0] < 2.5\n",
    "nonzero_quality_flags = lc_raw.quality != 0\n",
    "\n",
    "keep_indices = ~first_2p5_days & ~nonzero_quality_flags"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`lightkurve` supports indexing, slicing, and boolean masking just like `numpy`.  \n",
    "Here we use boolean masking to keep the samples devoid of quality flags and poor pointing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lc_trim = lc_raw[keep_indices]\n",
    "lc = lc_trim.normalize()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Instantiate and apply the SFF corrector."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sff = SFFCorrector()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lc_corrected = sff.correct(lc.time, lc.flux, lc.centroid_col, lc.centroid_row, \n",
    "                           niters=1, windows=1, polyorder=5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can get back the long-term trend, which is useful for astrophysical variation, but less so for planet searches.  \n",
    "Future `lightkurve` releases may return the trend by default."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "long_term_trend = sff.trend[0]"
   ]
